attributes.body:
It looks as if there are a number of lovely things to do here in La Paz. First off, I'm knocking some work out.

Already I'm noticing some differences from Peru. It's definitely much less oriented towards toursim. They really didn't go out of their way to make migration very easy or cheap. In Peru, as I recall, it was free. I arrived at the border and they told me that in order to enter their country I had to pay $135 USD. I was flabberghasted. It seemed to me that a country that didn't have a bunch of cash would want to encourage tourism... but, no. I paid the $135 reluctantly, not being sure if I was being had by some corrupt official. But, I did some research when I reached La Paz, and it turns out they single out Americans to pay a bunch of money at the border. If I were Canadian, I could enter for free. Stranger still, they wanted it in USD.

The city looks rather pretty in some parts. I'm excited to explore more.

photos.title: Death Road
photos.description: Didn't feel like stopping before this point. Turns out death road isn't all that deadly. Fun ride though!

photos.title: Strange Mountain Face
photos.description: This mountain face on the way to Death Road seemed odd to me.

photos.title: Valle De La Luna Panorama
photos.description: You can just see a little dude up atop a rock near the middle. He's playing a flute which echoes through the whole valley. Good idea, dude.

photos.title: Valle De La Luna - Valley of the Moon
photos.description: This is the valley of the moon, just south of La Paz. Erosion can do some pretty interesting things.

photos.title: Food Tour
photos.description: So much meat and french fries. Welcome to Bolivia!

photos.title: Llama Fetuses
photos.description: More dead llamas. Good luck apparently!

photos.title: Cholitas Choking
photos.description: Someone has to get choked by their own braids, or it isn't cholita wrestling.

photos.title: Cholita
photos.description: This was my favorite cholita wrestler. I couldn't get enough of this cutle little lady.

photos.title: Luchador
photos.description: Luchador wrester. This guys shape cracked me up.

photos.title: Windy Road
photos.description: This road winds quickly down into La Paz.

photos.title: TV Taxi
photos.description: This taxi plays music videos in the console.

photos.title: Tunnel
photos.description: Tunnel on the way home one night.

photos.title: Loud Music Warning
photos.description: These signs are required by law, basically telling you how long you can be in a bar with loud music without damaging your hearing. I found it sort of funny considering everyone still smokes in bars here.

photos.title: Shoeshine Painter
photos.description: Almost all of the shoeshine boys here wear ski masks, apparently it has something to do with being ashamed of their job, but it looks sort of creepy. Rather than a picture of the person, here's a picture of a mural of a person.

photos.title: Llama Fetuses
photos.description: These llama fetuses are supposedly for good luck.

photos.title: La Paz from Above
photos.description: My first glimpse of La Paz. The number of little boxes was boggling to the eye.

photos.title: La Paz from Above Panorama
photos.description: This gets a few more in there.

photos.title: The Barge
photos.description: Had to take a barge across Lake Titicaca. This was moments before the lighting and hail started. 20 Bolivianos for the ride across (a little under $3).

photos.title: Curve
photos.description: The road curves along Titicaca.

photos.title: Copacabana
photos.description: I rode around Copacabana and decided to stick to the road to La Paz.

photos.title: Silviu Florea
photos.description: Was riding in the opposite direction of Silviu, when he stopped me to give me a gas can (to save some cash in Bolivia, because locals can buy gas for about a third of the price.). Since he was heading to Peru, and I to Bolivia we swapped SIM cards, and some stories on the side of the road. He also gave me his map of Bolivia. It was really great running into someone on the road at such a perfect time.
